Question: My spouse earns income from freelance consulting and also receives a
  pension. How do I assess whether her total income falls under the
  threshold for me to remain entitled to the household allowance?
Example answer: The household allowance is payable only where the gross annual income
  of the member of staff's spouse or recognised partner does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. For this purpose, "gross annual income" is
  defined as income originating in the calendar year preceding that in
  respect of which eligibility is assessed, from employment or self-
  employment, from income replacement (e.g. maternity allowance,
  parental allowance, social security benefits and unemployment
  allowance, but not payments representing reimbursement of expenses),
  or from a pension, before tax and before the deduction of social
  security contributions; investment income and income from capital
  gains are not considered. Both the freelance consulting income and
  the pension would therefore count toward the threshold. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 9; ECB Staff Rules, page 63)
Predicted answer: - Determine the reference year: Use the calendar year preceding the
  year for which you’re assessing entitlement. - What to include as
  “gross annual income” for your spouse:   - Include: all freelance
  consulting (self-employment) income and all pension payments
  received in that year.   - Calculate both on a gross basis: before
  tax and before deduction of social security contributions.   - Also
  include any income-replacement benefits (e.g., unemployment
  allowance), if applicable.   - Exclude: investment income and
  capital gains, and any payments that are reimbursements of expenses.
  - Compare the total to EUR 71,764 (the threshold in Article 15 of
  the Conditions of Employment).   - If the total is at or below EUR
  71,764, you remain entitled to the household allowance (subject to
  other standard conditions).   - If it exceeds EUR 71,764, you are
  not entitled. - Keep evidence ready: provide the latest tax
  declaration and any relevant statements (e.g., pension statements,
  self-employment/tax assessments) as proof of income. - Note: If both
  spouses/recognised partners are ECB staff and both fall under the
  limit, the allowance is paid to the one with the higher salary.
