Question: I'm approaching the end of my ECB contract and have been notified that
  a cooling-off period applies, which prevents me from taking up the
  new role I had lined up. What financial support is available during
  that period?
Example answer: Certain staff intending to engage in a new occupational activity after
  the end of their ECB employment must refrain, for a specified
  cooling-off period, from any activity that could conflict with the
  ECB's interests. Staff who are prohibited as a result of that
  cooling-off period from undertaking a specific activity and who
  cannot find a suitable alternative and are consequently unemployed
  are entitled, for the duration of the prohibition, to a special
  monthly allowance of 80% of the last basic salary for the first year
  and 60% for the year thereafter, household and child allowances,
  continued cover under the ECB health, long-term care and accident
  insurance (subject to contributions), an education allowance capped
  at EUR 393 per month (or EUR 764 for certified imperative
  educational needs), and accrual of pensionable service. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, pages 3, 18–19)
Predicted answer: If your cooling-off period prevents you from taking up a role and you
  cannot find a suitable alternative job and are therefore unemployed,
  the ECB Conditions of Employment provide:  - Cooling-off specific
  entitlement (Article 36a): Under the conditions laid down in the
  Staff Rules, you are entitled to benefits for the duration of the
  prohibition on undertaking the activity and as long as you remain
  unemployed.  - General unemployment support (Article 36):   -
  Monthly unemployment allowance equal to:     - 60% of your last
  basic salary for six months; and     - 30% of your last basic salary
  for the subsequent six months and additional months in relation to
  years of service and age.   - Household and child allowances.   -
  Continued cover under ECB health insurance, long‑term care insurance
  and accident insurance, subject to payment of the relevant
  contributions.   - Education allowance in accordance with Article
  19: reimbursement up to EUR 393 per month (or up to EUR 764 per
  month for children with certified imperative educational needs as
  defined in the Staff Rules), payable only until the end of the
  academic year in which you become unemployed and provided the child
  remains eligible.  - One-off payment (Article 36): If you provide
  evidence of registration as unemployed and seeking employment
  through the competent employment authorities, you shall receive a
  one‑off payment equivalent to one month’s salary at Band A, step 1
  for each full year of service completed, with a minimum of three
  months and a maximum of twelve months of Band A, step 1.  -
  Coordination with other benefits (Article 36(e)): Any benefits of
  the same nature from other sources must be claimed and declared and
  will be deducted from amounts payable under this Article.
